title: For Sale:  Sig 551A1 Enhanced
postcontent: One of the nicest piston driven 5.56x45mm Semi-Auto rifles I've seen in some time. Sig took their time on this one and the 551A1 is the rifle that the American market wanted all along.  This rifle is almost like a product improved AK-47 Type rifle with the rotating bolt and long stroke gas piston.  The 55A1 uses the original Stgw-90 rock in magazines and has a melonite coated barrel. The finish is a grey cerakote that is very close to the original Sig 550 factory finish in color and appearance. These fine rifles are no longer in production by Sig Sauer and are rapidly becoming collector items.   This rifle also has been upgraded with the excellent MFI 550 Type Diopter sights w/fiber optic inserts, Manticore Arms POST, and an original Swiss Stgw-90 sling. The MFI Sights sit lower than the Sig USA sights at the level established by the Stge-90 / Sig 550 series of service rifles and are extremely fast to acquire.  Used in VG+ condition with minimal marks from use. Brass rash at ejection port and some dings on the front sight housing are visible. Internals are clean and smooth operating. No corrosion or pitting. Overall in really nice shape.  It is about as close to the Swiss Stgw-90 that is in currnet Swiss issue today that you can get in the USA without paying $10K for one of the few Semi-Auto versions that are floating around.Full album link:  551A1 Enhanced

title: For Sale:  Hard to Find Sig Sauer P238 HD California Legal with Laser
postcontent: I wound up with 2 of these pistols after the holidays and decided to sell this new, unfired, in the carrying case Sig Sauer California-legal P238 HD. I love the way it feels in my hand, and carrying it is easy because of its dinky size and light weight. This stainless mini-1911 pistol is one of the best, most accurate concealed carry pistols on the market. It has G10 polymer grips, a 6+1 round capacity and a 2.72" barrel. It is only 5.5" high by less than 4" long and weighs about 16 ounces with the magazine. Has thumb safety where the slide can move back and forth with the hammer cocked and the safety on. Recoil is minimal with standard .380 loads.  These pistols are hard to find in the California versions.  I removed the rear sight and added a red laser with a replacement rear sight.  It works beautifully. Comes with 1 magazine, mini-holster, lock, and original plastic case.

title: For Sale:  GSAD Golden State Arms AK47S, pre-pre-ban. Before Norinco, Clayco or Polytech
postcontent: Golden State Arms Dist. Inc ( GSAD ) Un-named AK47S. These were some of the first AKs to be brought to the US civilian market in the early 80s. This is a very early example with no roll mark or engraved importer markings, only a paint stamp that says "Golden State Arms Dist. Inc. Manhattan Beach, CA" The factory rollmark  reads "AK47S 7.62X39MM Made In China" This rifle was most likely made at the Jing An factory which at that time was tooled up for secret police and special forces type weapons. The fit and finish is much better than most of the combloc/chinese weapons we are familiar with. I bought this rifle right before the Clinton ban in 94 from an estate. This rifle is not "new in the box" it has a few safe dings but it is in great condition and has not seen much daylight. It has been fired about 50 rounds by me. Sadly I do not have the box. The sling, cleaning kit, cleaning rod and magazine are the ones I received with the rifle. Since it is such a rare example in such good shape I have never taken it out and abused it as I do with my "everyday" AKs. As much as I enjoy looking at it in the back of the safe after 22 years of proud ownership I am ready to cash her in for another project. I am not a photographer by trade and Armslist only allows three pics so feel free to send your email with questions.  Located in Russell but go to Wichita frequently, can meet FTF along the way (Ellsworth, Salina, McPherson, Hutchinson, etc...) $1800 CASH only, no trades other than towards CZ SP-01, Sig 556R or some 7.62 AK variants. title: For Sale:  WW I, Rem. MLE1907-15
postcontent: This is a very good condition WW I French infantry rifle (Remington Arms Corp. [RAC], model MLE 1907-15, made by Remington.   As far as I can tell, it is the 8mm Libel cartridge which you can still by ammo for.  It still has the original 31" barrel length with the bayonet attachment studs on the bottom of the muzzle.  Most of these you find have the barrels cut back shorter after the war.  The rifle still has a lot of bluing intact.  The bore is shinny, rifling is sharp and not a spec of rust in the bore.  It still has the flip up, long range sight as well.  For a seasoned collector or just someone wanting a nice piece of history, this would be a great piece.  I have not shot it, but the bolt and trigger function smoothly as they should.  Ammo is easy to find online.      These rifles were made by Remington in the USA and then shipped to the French to fight the Germans in World War One.  I inherited this from my father and thought I would pass it along to someone more interested in antique military rifles.  He took immaculate care of his guns so rest assured, this rifle is in great shape for its age.   Feel free to call or text with any questions, 205 5two7 nine713.  I have more detailed pics I can send.  The add only allows one picture.
